AppendNewLine(StringBuilder, String)

Appends the default line terminator followed by a copy of the specified string to the end of the current System.Text.StringBuilder object.

NOTE that this method differs from the System.Text.StringBuilder.AppendLine(System.String) in that it appends the line terminator before the specified string.

BiSplit(String, Char)

Splits this string into two substrings at the position where the first occurrence of separator is found.

This is a useful method when splitting an attribute-value string like "company: Microsoft".

Declaration
public static Pair<string> BiSplit(this string source, char separator)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.String source

This string instance.
System.Char separator

A character as the separator. NOTE that this separator will be removed. For example, split "abcde" by "c" and we will get "ab" and "de".
Returns
Type Description
Pair<System.String>

A pair of split substrings if the separator is found; otherwise, null.
| Improve this Doc View Source

BiSplit(String, Char, out String, out String)

Splits this string into two substrings at the position where the first occurrence of separator is found.

This is a useful method when splitting an attribute-value string like "company: Microsoft".

Declaration
public static bool BiSplit(this string source, char separator, out string first, out string second)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.String source

This string instance.
System.Char separator

A character as the separator. NOTE that this separator will be removed. For example, split "abcde" by "c" and we will get "ab" and "de".
System.String first

If separator is found, returns the substring from beginning to the position before separator, where System.String.Empty is returned if the leading character of the current string equals the separator; otherwise, null.
System.String second

If separator is found, returns the substring from the position after separator to the end; otherwise, null.
Returns
Type Description
System.Boolean

true if separator is found in the current string; otherwise, false.

Contains(String, String, Int32, Boolean, StringComparison)

Gets a value indicating whether the specified value occurs in this string instance after (or before, determined by fromBeginningToEnd) the specified zero-based position. This method allows you to set search direction and comparison options.

Declaration
public static bool Contains(this string str, string value, int startIndex, bool fromBeginningToEnd = true, StringComparison comparisonType = StringComparison.CurrentCulture)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.String str

This string instance.
System.String value

The string to seek.
System.Int32 startIndex

Indicating the zero-based position where the search starts.

Use -1 to indicate the default position. If fromBeginningToEnd is set true, the default position is 0; otherwise, the default position is the end of this string instance.
System.Boolean fromBeginningToEnd

Specifies the search direction. If this parameter is set true, the search starts at startIndex and ends at the end of this string instance; otherwise, the search starts at startIndex and proceeds toward the beginning of this string instance.
System.StringComparison comparisonType

Specifies the rules of search.
Returns
Type Description
System.Boolean

true if the target value occurs in this string instance after (or before, determined by fromBeginningToEnd) the specified position; otherwise, false
| Improve this Doc View Source

ContainsAllSequentially(String, IList<String>, Int32)

Determines whether this string instance contains all the specified strings sequentially.

** The difference between this method and ContainsAll is how the target values should occur. For example, string "ab, ef, cd" contains "ab", "cd" and "ef" but does not contain "ab", "cd" and "ef" sequentially.

Decorate(String, Char, Char, Int32, HorizontalAlignment, Int32, Boolean)

Decorates this string with the repetition of specified characters.

For example, decorating "abc" as "--abc***" when using "-" as the decoration character at the left side and "*" at the right side, or as " abc " when using a space as the decoration character at both sides.

Declaration
public static string Decorate(this string str, char leftDecorationChar, char rightDecorationChar, int totalLength, HorizontalAlignment alignment = HorizontalAlignment.Center, int indent = 0, bool rightLonger = false)
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.String str

A System.String object.
System.Char leftDecorationChar

The decoration character at the left side.
System.Char rightDecorationChar

The decoration character at the right side.
System.Int32 totalLength

The total length of the string plus the decoration.
HorizontalAlignment alignment

The alignment of this string.
System.Int32 indent

A positive integer indicates this string moves rightward; a negative integer indicates moving leftward.
System.Boolean rightLonger

Indicates whether the decoration at the right side can be longer than the other side when it is not possible to make them even.
Returns
Type Description
System.String

A string with decoration.
Remarks

Usage: this method could be useful in console applications or other scenarios to output aligned texts.

Test: this method has been tested, but is not guaranteed bug-free.

Future: future versions could use unsafe coding to improve performance.

| Improve this Doc View Source

Converts non-ASCII characters in this string instance to their ASCII equivalents wherever possible. For example, accents are removed from accented characters. One non-ASCII character may be converted to an equivalent of multiple ASCII characters.

GetComboEnumerator(String, Char, Char, Char, Char, Char, Char)

Gets an enumerator that can iterate through certain combinations of strings specified in this combination expression.

Declaration
public static IEnumerator<string[]> GetComboEnumerator(this string expression, char parameterGroupSeparator = ';', char parameterSeparator = ',', char parameterLeftBracket = '(', char parameterRightBracket = ')', char leftQuote = '[', char rightQuote = ']')
Parameters
Type Name Description
System.String expression

A combination expression to indicate what strings are used for combination and how they are combined.
System.Char parameterGroupSeparator

A Unicode character used as the separator to delimit different types of arguments.
System.Char parameterSeparator

A Unicode character used as the separator to delimit different arguments of the same type.
System.Char parameterLeftBracket

A Unicode character right paired by the parameterRightBracket to bracket the argument part.
System.Char parameterRightBracket

A Unicode character left paired by the parameterLeftBracket to bracket the argument part.
System.Char leftQuote

A Unicode character right paired by the rightQuote to escape parameterGroupSeparator and parameterSeparator.
System.Char rightQuote

A Unicode character left paired by the leftQuote to escape parameterGroupSeparator and parameterSeparator.
Returns
Type Description
System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerator<System.String[]>

An enumerator object that can be used to iterate through combinations of strings specified in the expression.
Remarks

A combination expression consists of two parts, the combination method and the bracketed argument part, which looks like "point(1,2,3)", where "point" is the combination method and "1,2,3" inside a pair of round brackets is the argument.

Three types of combination methods are supported.

    The cube method supports three types of argument besides the keywords.

      NOTE that the depth arguments and the count arguments are optional, and expressions like "cube(a,b,c; random)", "cube(a,b,c; 1-2; random)" are valid. Also NOTE that if the depth arguments are not specified, then the count arguments should not be used, for the count argument correspond to the depth arguments.
      | Improve this Doc View Source

      GetDoubleSplitEnumerator(String, Func<Char, Boolean>, Func<Char, Boolean>, Int32, Boolean, Boolean)

      Gets an object that can iterate through groups of substrings in this string instance (or a part of the current string instance according to startIndex) that are delimited by Unicode characters satisfying the specified primary predicate and secondary predicate.

      Declaration
      public static IEnumerator<string[]> GetDoubleSplitEnumerator(this string str, Func<char, bool> primaryPredicate, Func<char, bool> secondaryPredicate, int startIndex = 0, bool removeEmptyEntries = false, bool trim = false)
      Parameters
      Type Name Description
      System.String str

      This string instance.
      System.Func<System.Char, System.Boolean> primaryPredicate

      A function used to test each Unicode character of the current string. If a character passes this predicate, it returns a non-negative integer as the separator's index; otherwise, this function must return -1. Any character satisfying this predicate will be used as the primary separator. A primary spearator delimits substring arrays, for example, in "123,456;abc,def" which represent substring arrays { {"123", "456"}, {"abc", "def"} }, the semi-comma ';' is the primary separator.
      System.Func<System.Char, System.Boolean> secondaryPredicate

      A function used to test each Unicode character of the current string. If a character passes this predicate, it returns a non-negative integer as the separator's index; otherwise, this function must return -1. Any character satisfying this predicate will be used as the secondary separator. A secondary separator delimits substrings in an array, for example, in "123,456;abc,def" which represent substring arrays { {"123", "456"}, {"abc", "def"} }, the comma ',' is the secondary separator.
      System.Int32 startIndex

      The zero-based position indicating where the search for separators starts.
      System.Boolean removeEmptyEntries

      true if the returned enumerator should ignore empty substrings; otherwise false.
      System.Boolean trim

      Indicates whether the returned substrings are trimmed.

      NOTE that if removeEmptyEntries is set true, then a substring containing only white spaces will be ignored by the returned enumerator; for example, in this case "123, ,456;abc,def" split by comma ';' (primary separator) and ',' (secondary separator) is { {"123", "456"}, {"abc", "def"} }.
      Returns
      Type Description
      System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerator<System.String[]>

      An object that can iterate through groups of substrings in this string instance (or a part of the current string instance) that are delimited by Unicode characters satisfying the specified two predicates.
      | Improve this Doc View Source

      GetDoubleSplitEnumeratorWithQuotes(String, Char, Char, Char, Char, Boolean, Boolean, Boolean, Boolean)

      Gets an object that can iterate through groups of substrings in this string instance that are delimited by the primary and secondary Unicode separators outside quotes.

      Declaration
      public static IEnumerator<string[]> GetDoubleSplitEnumeratorWithQuotes(this string str, char primarySeparator, char secondarySeparator, char leftQuote = '{', char rightQuote = '}', bool removeEmptyEntries = false, bool removeEmptyGroups = false, bool trim = false, bool keepQuotes = true)
      Parameters
      Type Name Description
      System.String str

      This string instance.
      System.Char primarySeparator

      A primary spearator delimits substring groups, for example, in "123,456;abc,def" which represent substring arrays { {"123", "456"}, {"abc", "def"} }, the semi-comma ';' is the primary separator.
      System.Char secondarySeparator

      A secondary separator delimits substrings in a group, for example, in "123,456;abc,def" which represent substring arrays { {"123", "456"}, {"abc", "def"} }, the comma ',' is the secondary separator.
      System.Char leftQuote

      The left quote paired by rightQuote to escape separators.
      System.Char rightQuote

      The right quote paired by leftQuote to escape separators.
      System.Boolean removeEmptyEntries

      true if empty strings should be ignored; otherwise false.
      System.Boolean removeEmptyGroups

      true if empty substring groups should be ignored by the returned enumerator; otherwise, false.
      System.Boolean trim

      Indicates whether the returned substrings are trimmed.

      NOTE that if removeEmptyEntries is set true, then a substring containing only white spaces will be ignored by the returned enumerator; for example, in this case "ab, ,cd" split by comma ',' is "ab" and "cd".
      System.Boolean keepQuotes

      true if the quotes should be included in each returned substring; otherwise, false.
      Returns

      Gets an object that can iterate through groups of substrings in this string instance (or a part of the current string instance according to startIndex and length) that are delimited by the primary and secondary Unicode separators outside quotes.

      Declaration
      public static IEnumerator<string[]> GetDoubleSplitEnumeratorWithQuotes(this string str, char primarySeparator, char secondarySeparator, int startIndex, int length, char leftQuote = '{', char rightQuote = '}', bool removeEmptyEntries = false, bool removeEmptyGroups = false, bool trim = false, bool keepQuotes = true)
      Parameters
      Type Name Description
      System.String str

      This string instance.
      System.Char primarySeparator

      A primary spearator delimits substring groups, for example, in "123,456;abc,def" which represent substring arrays { {"123", "456"}, {"abc", "def"} }, the semi-comma ';' is the primary separator.
      System.Char secondarySeparator

      A secondary separator delimits substrings in a group, for example, in "123,456;abc,def" which represent substring arrays { {"123", "456"}, {"abc", "def"} }, the comma ',' is the secondary separator.
      System.Int32 startIndex

      The zero-based position indicating where the search for separators starts.
      System.Int32 length

      A positive value indicating the number of characters to search starting from the position specified by startIndex.
      System.Char leftQuote

      The left quote paired by rightQuote to escape separators.
      System.Char rightQuote

      The right quote paired by leftQuote to escape separators.
      System.Boolean removeEmptyEntries

      true if empty strings should be ignored; otherwise false.
      System.Boolean removeEmptyGroups

      true if empty substring groups should be ignored by the returned enumerator; otherwise, false.
      System.Boolean trim

      Indicates whether the returned substrings are trimmed.

      NOTE that if removeEmptyEntries is set true, then a substring containing only white spaces will be ignored by the returned enumerator; for example, in this case "ab, ,cd" split by comma ',' is "ab" and "cd".
      System.Boolean keepQuotes

      true if the quotes should be included in each returned substring; otherwise, false.

      Parameters
      Type Name Description
      System.String str

      This string instance.
      System.Func<System.Char, System.Boolean> primaryPredicate

      A function used to test each Unicode character of the current string. If a character passes this predicate, it returns a non-negative integer as the separator's index; otherwise, this function must return -1. Any character satisfying this predicate will be used as the primary separator. A primary spearator delimits substring arrays, for example, in "123,456;abc,def" which represent substring arrays { {"123", "456"}, {"abc", "def"} }, the semi-comma ';' is the primary separator.
      System.Func<System.Char, System.Boolean> secondaryPredicate

      A function used to test each Unicode character of the current string. If a character passes this predicate, it returns a non-negative integer as the separator's index; otherwise, this function must return -1. Any character satisfying this predicate will be used as the secondary separator. A secondary separator delimits substrings in an array, for example, in "123,456;abc,def" which represent substring arrays { {"123", "456"}, {"abc", "def"} }, the comma ',' is the secondary separator.
      System.Char leftQuote

      The left quote paired by rightQuote to escape separators.
      System.Char rightQuote

      The right quote paired by leftQuote to escape separators.

      true if empty strings should be ignored; otherwise false.

      System.Boolean keepQuotes

      true if the quotes should be included in each returned substring; otherwise, false.

      GetKeyValuePairEnumerator(String, Char, Char, Char, Char, Boolean)

      Gets an enumerator that iterates through key/value pairs represented by this string instance, if this string follows certain syntax.

      Declaration
      public static IEnumerator<KeyValuePair<string, string>> GetKeyValuePairEnumerator(this string expression, char keyDelimiter = '=', char pairDelimiter = ';', char leftQuote = '[', char rightQuote = ']', bool trimValue = true)
      Parameters
      Type Name Description
      System.String expression

      This string instance.
      System.Char keyDelimiter

      The Unicode character that delimits key and value in each pair. In each pair, only the first character that equals this argument will be recognized as a delimiter, and it cannot be escaped.
      System.Char pairDelimiter

      The Unicode character that delimits key/value pairs. This delimiter is escapable.
      System.Char leftQuote

      The Unicode character as the left escape quote for pairDelimiter. Use '\0' to indicate the escape is disabled and all three argument leftQuote, rightQuote and escape are ineffective.
      System.Char rightQuote

      The Unicode character as the right escape quote for pairDelimiter.
      System.Boolean trimValue

      true if the white spaces at both ends of the value of each returned pair is trimmed; otherwise, false.
      Returns
      Type Description
      System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerator<System.Collections.Generic.KeyValuePair<System.String, System.String>>

      An enumerator that iterates through key/value pairs represented by this string instance.
      Remarks

      This string must follow the syntax "(<key> <keyDelimiter> <leftQuote>?<value> <pairDelimiter><rightQuote>?) (...n)" If the pairDelimiter is ';' (default value) and the escape is disabled, this string must follow the syntax "(<key> = <value>;) (...n)" which is exactly the same as a standard database connection string.

      | Improve this Doc View Source

      GetSplitEnumerator(String, Char, Boolean, Boolean, Boolean)

      Gets an object that can iterate through substrings in this string that are delimited by the specified Unicode character.

      Declaration
      public static IEnumerator<string> GetSplitEnumerator(this string str, char separator, bool removeEmptyEntries = false, bool trim = false, bool keepSeparator = false)
      Parameters
      Type Name Description
      System.String str

      This string instance.
      System.Char separator

      A Unicode character that delimits the substrings in the current string instance.
      System.Boolean removeEmptyEntries

      true if the returned enumerator should ignore empty substrings; otherwise false.
      System.Boolean trim

      Indicates whether the returned substrings are trimmed.

      NOTE if removeEmptyEntries is set true, then a substring containing only white spaces will be ignored by the returned enumerator; for example, in this case "ab, ,cd" split by comma ',' is "ab" and "cd".
      System.Boolean keepSeparator

      true if the separator should be included in each substring returned by the enumerator; otherwise, false.
      Returns
      Type Description
      System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerator<System.String>

      An object that can iterate through substrings in the current string instance (or a part of the current string instance) that are delimited by the specified Unicode character.
      | Improve this Doc View Source

      Gets an object that can iterate through information about substrings in this string instance that are delimited by Unicode characters satisfying the specified predicate.

      Declaration
      public static IEnumerator<StringSplitResult> GetSplitEnumeratorEx(this string str, Func<char, int> predicate, bool removeEmptyEntries = false, bool trim = false)
      Parameters
      Type Name Description
      System.String str

      This string instance.
      System.Func<System.Char, System.Int32> predicate

      A function used to test each Unicode character of the current string. If a character passes this predicate, it returns a non-negative integer as the separator's index; otherwise, this function must return -1. Any character satisfying this predicate will be used as the separator.
      System.Boolean removeEmptyEntries

      true if the returned enumerator should ignore empty substrings; otherwise false.
      System.Boolean trim

      Indicates whether the returned substrings are trimmed.

      NOTE that if removeEmptyEntries is set true, then a substring containing only white spaces will not be returned; for example, in this case "ab, ,cd" split by comma ',' is "ab" and "cd".
      Returns
      Type Description
      System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerator<StringSplitResult>

      An object that can iterate through information about substrings in the current string instance that are delimited by Unicode characters satisfying the specified predicate.
      | Improve this Doc View Source

      GetSplitEnumeratorWithQuotes(String, Char, Char, Char, Boolean, Boolean, Boolean, Boolean)

      Gets an object that can iterate through substrings in this string instance that are delimited by Unicode separators outside quotes.

      Declaration
      public static IEnumerator<string> GetSplitEnumeratorWithQuotes(this string str, char separator, char leftQuote = '{', char rightQuote = '}', bool removeEmptyEntries = false, bool trim = false, bool keepQuotes = true, bool keepSeparator = false)
      Parameters
      Type Name Description
      System.String str

      This string instance.
      System.Char separator

      The separator.
      System.Char leftQuote

      The left quote paired by rightQuote to escape separators.
      System.Char rightQuote

      The right quote paired by leftQuote to escape separators.
      System.Boolean removeEmptyEntries

      true if empty strings should be removed from the returned substrings; otherwise false.
      System.Boolean trim

      Indicates whether the returned substrings are trimmed.

      NOTE that if removeEmptyEntries is set true, then a substring containing only white spaces will be ignored by the returned enumerator; for example, in this case "ab, ,cd" split by comma ',' is "ab" and "cd".
      System.Boolean keepQuotes

      true if the quotes should be included in each returned substring; otherwise, false.
      System.Boolean keepSeparator

      true if the separator should be included in each returned substring; otherwise, false.
      Returns
      Type Description
      System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerator<System.String>

      An object that can iterate through substrings in the current string instance that are delimited by Unicode characters outside quotes.
      Exceptions
      Type Condition
      System.FormatException

      Occurs when there is a quote mismatch in the string instance.
      | Improve this Doc View Source

      System.Boolean removeEmptyEntries

      true if empty strings should be removed from the returned substrings; otherwise false.
      System.Boolean trim

      Indicates whether the returned substrings are trimmed.

      NOTE that if removeEmptyEntries is set true, then a substring containing only white spaces will be ignored by the returned enumerator; for example, in this case "ab, ,cd" split by comma ',' is "ab" and "cd".

      true if the quotes should be included in each returned substring; otherwise, false.
      System.Boolean keepSeparator

      true if the separator should be included in each returned substring; otherwise, false.

      Any character in this array will be used as a separator.
      System.Int32 startIndex

      The zero-based position indicating where the search for separators starts.
      System.Int32 length

      A positive value indicating the number of characters to search starting from the position specified by startIndex.
      System.Char[] leftQuotes

      Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the left quotes. A left quote of an index of this array corresponds to the right quote of that index of the array specified by rightQuotes.
      System.Char[] rightQuotes

      Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the right quotes. A right quote of an index of this array corresponds to the left quote of that index of the array specified by leftQuotes.
      System.Boolean removeEmptyEntries

      true if empty strings should be removed from the returned substrings; otherwise false.
      System.Boolean trim

      Indicates whether the returned substrings are trimmed.

      NOTE that if removeEmptyEntries is set true, then a substring containing only white spaces will be ignored by the returned enumerator; for example, in this case "ab, ,cd" split by comma ',' is "ab" and "cd".
      System.Boolean keepQuotes

      true if the quotes should be included in each returned substring; otherwise, false.
      System.Boolean keepSeparator

      true if the separator should be included in each returned substring; otherwise, false.
      Returns
      Type Description
      System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerator<System.String>

      An object that can iterate through substrings in the current string instance (or a part of the current string instance) that are delimited by Unicode characters outside quotes.
      Exceptions
      Type Condition
      System.FormatException

      Occurs when there is a quote mismatch in the string instance.

      HexEncode(String, Encoding, Char)

      Encodes non-ASCII chars in this string by their equivalent hex representations.

      ** Particularly used in translating url containing non-ASCII chars to an ASCII url. For example, "http://www.hudong.com/wiki/电子垃圾" will be translated to "http://www.hudong.com/wiki/%E7%94%B5%E5%AD%90%E5%9E%83%E5%9C%BE".

      Declaration

      System.Char byteIndicator

      Specifies the char before each hex representation of a byte value.
      Returns
      Type Description
      System.String

      A copy of the original string with all non-ASCII chars and the chars in the exception list converted to hex representations.
      | Improve this Doc View Source

      Declaration
      public static int IndexOfAnyWithQuotes(this string str, char[] values, char primaryLeftQuote, char primaryRightQuote, char secondaryLeftQuote, char secondaryRightQuote)
      Parameters
      Type Name Description
      System.String str

      This string instance.
      System.Char[] values

      The Unicode characters to seek.
      System.Char primaryLeftQuote

      Specifies the Unicode character as the primary left quote.
      System.Char primaryRightQuote

      Specifies the Unicode character as the primary right quote.
      System.Char secondaryLeftQuote

      Specifies the Unicode character as the secondary left quote. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.

      Specifies the Unicode character as the secondary right quote. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.

      Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the primary left quotes. A left quote of an index of this array corresponds to the right quote of that index of the array specified by primaryRightQuotes.
      System.Char[] primaryRightQuotes

      Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the primary right quotes. A right quote of an index of this array corresponds to the left quote of that index of the array specified by primaryLeftQuotes.
      System.Char secondaryLeftQuote

      Specifies the Unicode character as the secondary left quote. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
      System.Char secondaryRightQuote

      Specifies the Unicode character as the secondary right quote. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.

      Type Description
      System.Int32

      The zero-based index position of the first occurrence of any value specified in values if it is found outside quotes, or -1 if it is not.

      Type Condition
      System.FormatException

      Occurs when there is a quote mismatch in the string instance.

      IndexOfNextMatch(String, Char, Char, Char, Char, Int32)

      Reports the zero-based index of the next character which matches another specified character outside quotes. Those matched characters are usually brackets, such as '(' and ')', '[' and ']', '{' and '}'.

      Declaration
      public static int IndexOfNextMatch(this string str, char leftChar, char rightChar, char leftQuote, char rightQuote, int startIndex = 0)
      Parameters
      Type Name Description
      System.String str

      This string instance.
      System.Char leftChar

      The character that matches the character to search, typically a left bracket, such as '(', '[' or '{'.
      System.Char rightChar

      The next character to search, typically a right bracket, such as ')', ']' or '}'.
      System.Char leftQuote

      Specifies the left quote. Any character inside quotes (leftQuote and rightQuote) will not be considered as a match.
      System.Char rightQuote

      Specifies the right quote. Any character inside quotes (leftQuote and rightQuote) will not be considered as a match.
      System.Int32 startIndex

      The search starting position. NOTE that this position should be right at the leftChar you want to find a match for. For example, if it is intended to find a match of the first left square bracket at position 0 in string "[abc[de]fgh]", the startIndex should be 0.
      Returns
      Type Description
      System.Int32

      The zero-based index position of rightChar if that character is found and it matches leftChar, or -1 if it is not.
      | Improve this Doc View Source

      IndexOfNextMatch(String, Char, Char, Char, Int32)

      Reports the zero-based index of the next character which matches another specified character. The method supports classic escaping. Those matched characters are usually brackets, such as '(' and ')', '[' and ']', '{' and '}'.

      Declaration
      public static int IndexOfNextMatch(this string str, char leftChar, char rightChar, char escape, int startIndex = 0)
      Parameters
      Type Name Description
      System.String str

      This string instance.
      System.Char leftChar

      The character that matches the character to search, typically a left bracket, such as '(', '[' or '{'.
      System.Char rightChar

      The next character to search, typically a right bracket, such as ')', ']' or '}'.
      System.Char escape

      The character that escapes the rightChar, typically '&apos;. For example, suppose '&apos; is used for escaping, then the match for the first left square bracket in string "[abc]abc]" is the last right square bracket, not the one in the middle because the '&apos; that precedes it escapes it.
      System.Int32 startIndex

      The search starting position. NOTE that this position should be right at the leftChar you want to find a match for. For example, if it is intended to find a match of the first left square bracket at position 0 in string "[abc[de]fgh]", the startIndex should be 0.
      Returns
      Type Description
      System.Int32

      The zero-based index position of rightChar if that character is found and it matches leftChar, or -1 if it is not.
      | Improve this Doc View Source

      Declaration
      public static int IndexOfNextMatch(this string str, char leftChar, char rightChar, char escape, int startIndex, int length)

      The character that escapes the rightChar, typically '&apos;. For example, suppose '&apos; is used for escaping, then the match for the first left square bracket in string "[abc]abc]" is the last right square bracket, not the one in the middle because the '&apos; that precedes it escapes it.

      The search starting position. NOTE that this position should be right at the leftChar you want to find a match for. For example, if it is intended to find a match of the first left square bracket at position 0 in string "[abc[de]fgh]", the startIndex should be 0.

      IndexOfNextMatch(String, Char, Char, Char[], Char[], Int32)

      Reports the zero-based index of the next character which matches another specified character outside quotes. Those matched characters are usually brackets, such as '(' and ')', '[' and ']', '{' and '}'.

      Declaration
      public static int IndexOfNextMatch(this string str, char leftChar, char rightChar, char[] leftQuotes, char[] rightQuotes, int startIndex = 0)
      Parameters
      Type Name Description
      System.String str

      This string instance.
      System.Char leftChar

      The character that matches the character to search, typically a left bracket, such as '(', '[' or '{'.
      System.Char rightChar

      The next character to search, typically a right bracket, such as ')', ']' or '}'.
      System.Char[] leftQuotes

      Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the left quotes. A left quote of an index of this array corresponds to the right quote of that index of the array specified by rightQuotes. Any character that appears between a left quote and its corresponding right quote will not be considered a match.
      System.Char[] rightQuotes

      Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the right quotes. A right quote of an index of this array corresponds to the left quote of that index of the array specified by leftQuotes. Any character that appears between a left quote and its corresponding right quote will not be considered a match.
      System.Int32 startIndex

      The search starting position. NOTE that this position should be right at the leftChar you want to find a match for. For example, if it is intended to find a match of the first left square bracket at position 0 in string "[abc[de]fgh]", the startIndex should be 0.
      Returns
      Type Description
      System.Int32

      The zero-based index position of rightChar if that character is found and it matches leftChar, or -1 if it is not.
      Exceptions
      Type Condition
      System.ArgumentOutOfRangeException

      Occurs if startIndex or startIndex + length does not indicate a valid position in the string.
      | Improve this Doc View Source

      System.Char primaryRightQuote

      Specifies the Unicode character as the primary right quote.
      System.Char[] secondaryLeftQuotes

      Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the secondary left quotes. A left quote of an index of this array corresponds to the right quote of that index of the array specified by secondaryRightQuotes. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
      System.Char[] secondaryRightQuotes

      Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the secondary right quotes. A right quote of an index of this array corresponds to the left quote of that index of the array specified by secondaryLeftQuotes. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
      Returns
      Type Description
      System.Int32

      The zero-based index position of the first Unicode character outside quotes and satisfying the specified predicate, or -1 if no such character is not.

      System.Char[] secondaryLeftQuotes

      Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the secondary left quotes. A left quote of an index of this array corresponds to the right quote of that index of the array specified by secondaryRightQuotes. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
      System.Char[] secondaryRightQuotes

      Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the secondary right quotes. A right quote of an index of this array corresponds to the left quote of that index of the array specified by secondaryLeftQuotes. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.
      System.StringComparison comparisonType

      One of the enumeration values that specifies the rules for the search of values.
      Returns
      Type Description
      StringSearchResult

      A StringSearchResult object that stores the zero-based index position of the last occurrence of any of the specified values if one is found outside quotes, or null if none is found.

      Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the secondary right quotes. A right quote of an index of this array corresponds to the left quote of that index of the array specified by secondaryLeftQuotes. Secondary quotes are escaped when they are inside a pair of primary quotes.

      Type Description
      System.Int32

      The zero-based index position of the last occurrence of value if it is found outside quotes, or -1 if it is not.

      The substring to seek.

      A positive value indicating the number of characters to search starting from position specified by startIndex towards the beginning of the current string.
      System.Char[] primaryLeftQuotes

      Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the primary left quotes. A left quote of an index of this array corresponds to the right quote of that index of the array specified by primaryRightQuote.
      System.Char[] primaryRightQuotes

      Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the primary right quotes. A right quote of an index of this array corresponds to the left quote of that index of the array specified by primaryLeftQuote.

      Remove(String, String[], Boolean)

      Removes a new string in which all occurrences of the specified substrings are removed from the current string. NOTE that this method only removes occurrences in the current string before the removal operation. Any new occurrence caused by the removal operation will not be removed again. For example, removing "ab", "bc" from "aabbcb" returns "ab".

      RemoveMatchedCharPair(String, Char, Char, Boolean)

      If the current string starts with the specified leftChr and ends with the specified rightChr, returns a new string instance with the leftChr and rightChr removed.

      Declaration
      public static string RemoveMatchedCharPair(this string str, char leftChr, char rightChr, bool ignoreWhitespace = true)
      Parameters
      Type Name Description
      System.String str

      This string instance.
      System.Char leftChr

      Checks if this System.Char appears at the beginning of the current string.
      System.Char rightChr

      Checks if this System.Char appears at the end of the current string.
      System.Boolean ignoreWhitespace

      If set to true, the white spaces defined by System.Char.IsWhiteSpace(System.Char) at the beginning and the end of the current string will be ignored. These white spaces will also be removed if a match of leftChr and rightChr are found.
      Returns
      Type Description
      System.String

      A new string instance with the leftChr at the beginning and the rightChr at the end removed; the original string instance if either leftChr is not found at the beginning of the current instance, or rightChr is not found at the end of the current instance. White spaces at the beginning and the end will also be removed if ignoreWhitespace is specified true.
      | Improve this Doc View Source

      Replace(String, String, String, Int32, Int32, out Int32)

      Returns a new string (except the case when no replacements are made and the original string is returned) in which all occurrences of a specified string in the specified searching scope of this instance are replaced with another specified string. The search for substrings uses case-sensitive rules and the current culture.

      Declaration
      public static string Replace(this string str, string oldValue, string newValue, int startIndex, int length, out int countOfReplacements)
      Parameters
      Type Name Description
      System.String str

      This string instance.
      System.String oldValue

      The string to be replaced.
      System.String newValue

      The string to replace the occurrences of oldValue.
      System.Int32 startIndex

      The search starting position.
      System.Int32 length

      The number of characters to search. The parameter determines the search ending position along with startIndex.
      System.Int32 countOfReplacements

      Returns the number of replacements that are made.
      Returns
      Type Description
      System.String

      A string that is equivalent to the current string except that all instances of oldValue are replaced with newValue in the specified searching scope.
      Exceptions
      Type Condition
      System.ArgumentOutOfRangeException

      Occurs if startIndex or startIndex + length does not indicate a valid position in the string.
      | Improve this Doc View Source

      ReplaceOrdinal(String, String, String, Int32)

      Returns a new string (except the case when no replacements are made and the original string is returned) in which all occurrences of a specified string in the specified searching scope of this instance are replaced with another specified string. The search for substrings uses case-sensitive ordinal rules. Use this method to perform fast and linguistically independent replaces.

      Declaration
      public static string ReplaceOrdinal(this string str, string oldValue, string newValue, int startIndex = 0)
      Parameters
      Type Name Description
      System.String str

      This string instance.
      System.String oldValue

      The string to be replaced.
      System.String newValue

      The string to replace the occurrences of oldValue.
      System.Int32 startIndex

      The search starting position.
      Returns
      Type Description
      System.String

      A string that is equivalent to the current string except that all instances of oldValue are replaced with newValue in the specified searching scope.
      Exceptions
      Type Condition
      System.ArgumentOutOfRangeException

      Occurs if startIndex or startIndex + length does not indicate a valid position in the string.
      | Improve this Doc View Source

      Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the left quotes. A left quote of an index of this array corresponds to the right quote of that index of the array specified by rightQuotes.
      System.Char[] rightQuotes

      Specifies an array of Unicode characters as the right quotes. A right quote of an index of this array corresponds to the left quote of that index of the array specified by leftQuotes.
      System.StringComparison comparisonType

      One of the enumeration values that specifies the rules for the search of oldValue.
      Returns
      Type Description
      System.String

      A new string instance with substrings replaced.
      Exceptions
      Type Condition
      System.FormatException

      Occurs when there is a quote mismatch in the string instance.
      | Improve this Doc View Source

      Retrieve(String, Int32, String, String, StringRetrievalOption[])

      Retrieves substrings represented by System.Substring objects from this string instance. The search proceeds accroding to the indicators in the System.RetrieveOption objects.

      This method first retrieves the an array of substrings according to the indicators in the first System.RetrieveOption object. If the previous search ends at position p1, then this method continutes to retrieve the second array of substrings according to the indicators in the second System.RetrieveOption object, starting from the postion p1.

      Declaration

      Split(String, Char, Boolean, Boolean, Boolean)

      Returns substrings of this string delimited by specified Unicode character. Additional options, such as string trimming, or separator keep, are available.

      Declaration
      public static string[] Split(this string str, char separator, bool removeEmptyEntries = false, bool trim = false, bool keepSeparator = false)
      Parameters
      Type Name Description
      System.String str

      This string instance.
      System.Char separator

      A Unicode characters that delimits the substrings in the current string instance.
      System.Boolean removeEmptyEntries

      true if empty strings should be removed from the returned substrings; otherwise false.
      System.Boolean trim

      Indicates whether the returned substrings should be trimmed.

      NOTE that if removeEmptyEntries is set true, then a substring containing only white spaces will not be returned; for example, in this case "ab, ,cd" split by comma ',' is "ab" and "cd".
      System.Boolean keepSeparator

      true if the separator should be included in each returned substring; otherwise, false.
      Returns
      Type Description
      System.String[]

      An array containing substrings of this string that are delimited by the specified separator.
      | Improve this Doc View Source

      Split(String, Char, Char, StringSplitOptions)

      Splits this string instance into a two-dimensional jagged array string[][]. For example, you may split "ab,c,defg;h,ijk;l,mn,op,q" with ',' as the separator1 and ';' the separator2. The result is three arrays of strings, the first one bing string array {"ab", "c", "defg"}.

      Declaration
      public static string[][] Split(this string str, char separator1, char separator2, StringSplitOptions options)
      Parameters
      Type Name Description
      System.String str

      This string instance.
      System.Char separator1

      The separator to split each string of the results from spliting the current string by separator2.
      System.Char separator2

      The separator to split the current string into a string array each of which will be then split by separator1.
      System.StringSplitOptions options

      Specifies whether the empty entries should be returned.
      Returns
      Type Description
      System.String[][]

      A two-dimensional jagged array storing the split result.

      Split(String, Func<Char, Boolean>, Boolean, Boolean, Boolean)

      Returns a string array that contains the substrings in this string that are delimited by characters satisfying the specified predicate.

      Declaration
      public static string[] Split(this string str, Func<char, bool> predicate, bool removeEmptyEntries = false, bool trim = false, bool keepSeparator = false)
      Parameters
      Type Name Description
      System.String str

      This string instance.
      System.Func<System.Char, System.Boolean> predicate

      A function to test each Unicode character of the current string. Any character satisfying this preidcate will be used as a separator.
      System.Boolean removeEmptyEntries

      true if empty strings should be removed from the returned substrings; otherwise false.
      System.Boolean trim

      Indicates whether the returned substrings are trimmed.

      NOTE that if removeEmptyEntries is set true, then a substring containing only white spaces will not be returned; for example, in this case "ab, ,cd" split by comma ',' is "ab" and "cd".
      System.Boolean keepSeparator

      true if the separator should be included in each returned substring; otherwise, false.
      Returns

      Split(String, Func<Char, Boolean>, Int32, Boolean, Boolean, Boolean)

      Returns a string array that contains the substrings in this string (or a part of this string according to startIndex) that are delimited by characters satisfying the specified predicate. Additional options, such as string trimming, or separator keep, are available.

      Declaration
      public static string[] Split(this string str, Func<char, bool> predicate, int startIndex, bool removeEmptyEntries = false, bool trim = false, bool keepSeparator = false)
      Parameters
      Type Name Description
      System.String str

      This string instance.
      System.Func<System.Char, System.Boolean> predicate

      A function to test each Unicode character of the current string. Any character satisfying this preidcate will be used as a separator.
      System.Int32 startIndex

      The zero-based position indicating where the search for separators starts.
      System.Boolean removeEmptyEntries

      true if empty strings should be removed from the returned substrings; otherwise false.
      System.Boolean trim

      Indicates whether the returned substrings are trimmed.

      NOTE that if removeEmptyEntries is set true, then a substring containing only white spaces will not be returned; for example, in this case "ab, ,cd" split by comma ',' is "ab" and "cd".
      System.Boolean keepSeparator

      true if the separator should be included in each returned substring; otherwise, false.
      Returns
      Type Description
      System.String[]

      An array containing substrings of this string (or part of this string) that are delimited by characters satisfying predicate.
      | Improve this Doc View Source

      Declaration
      public static StringSplitResult[] SplitEx(this string str, Func<char, int> predicate, int startIndex, bool removeEmptyEntries = false, bool trim = false)
      Parameters

      System.String str

      This string instance.

      true if empty strings should be removed from the returned substrings; otherwise false.

      SplitWithQuotes(String, Char, Int32, Char, Char, Boolean, Boolean, Boolean)

      Returns a string array that contains the substrings in this string (or a part of this string) that are delimited by specified Unicode characters outside quotes.

      Declaration
      public static string[] SplitWithQuotes(this string str, char separator, int startIndex = 0, char leftQuote = '{', char rightQuote = '}', bool removeEmptyEntries = true, bool keepQuotes = true, bool keepSeparator = false)
      Parameters
      Type Name Description
      System.String str

      This string instance.
      System.Char separator

      A Unicode characters that delimits the substrings in the current string instance.
      System.Int32 startIndex

      The zero-based position indicating where the search for the separator starts.
      System.Char leftQuote

      Specifies the Unicode character as the left quote.
      System.Char rightQuote

      Specifies the Unicode character as the right quote.
      System.Boolean removeEmptyEntries

      true if empty strings should be removed from the returned substrings; otherwise false.
      System.Boolean keepQuotes

      true if the quotes are not removed in the returned strings. For example, splitting string "{a,b},c" by comma ',' with '{' and '}' as the quotes produces array "{a,b}", "c" with this argument set true, and "a,b", "c" with this argument set false.
      System.Boolean keepSeparator

      true if the separator is not removed from the returned strings. For example, splitting string "a,b,c" by comma ',' produces "a,", "b,", "c" with this argument set true and "a", "b", "c" without this argument set false.
      Returns
      Type Description
      System.String[]

      A string array whose elements are the substrings in the current string instance (or a part of the current string instance) that are delimited by the outside-quote separator.
      | Improve this Doc View Source

      Specifies the Unicode character as the left quote.
      System.Char rightQuote

      Specifies the Unicode character as the right quote.
      System.Boolean removeEmptyEntries

      true if empty strings should be removed from the returned substrings; otherwise false.
      System.Boolean keepQuotes

      true if the quotes are not removed in the returned strings. For example, splitting string "{a,b},c" by comma ',' with '{' and '}' as the quotes produces array "{a,b}", "c" with this argument set true, and "a,b", "c" with this argument set false.
      System.Boolean keepSeparator

      true if separators are not removed from the returned strings. For example, splitting string "a,b,c" by comma ',' produces "a,", "b,", "c" with this argument set true and "a", "b", "c" without this argument set false.
      Returns
      Type Description
      StringSplitResult[]

      A StringSplitResult array that contains information about the substrings in the current string instance (or a part of the current string instance) that are delimited by outside-quote separators.
      | Improve this Doc View Source
